1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
 ♪ Beautiful dream away, come to me ♪

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,000
 ♪ Starlight and you drop ♪

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:13,000
 ♪ Awaiting for thee ♪

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 Hello, this is Maria from dresspattingmaking.com.

5
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,000
 In this video, I'm going to walk you through how to draft the pants block.

6
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:24,000
 I'll be drafting the pants front first, as the front is used to help draft the back.

7
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 This is part two with three videos on drafting the pants block.

8
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:32,000
 In these videos, I go through drafting the pants for four different figure shapes, as shown below.

9
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 The step-by-step instructions are the same for all figure types up to a certain point,

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:39,000
 but when we add to shaping the waist and getting the crotch length right,

11
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:44,000
 is where I bring in the other figure types and show how to make the necessary adjustments.

12
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
 Part one of these three videos is the introduction and covers measurements.

13
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:52,000
 The details about the figure shapes shown below and what I mean by "standard" is covered in part one.

14
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,000
 If you have tried other pant making instructions in the past

15
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:57,000
 and are puzzled why you don't get a good fit,

16
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 part one also explains the assumptions that are built into most block making instructions which assume a standard figure.

17
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:10,000
 The second half of part one covers the measurements you will need to draft the pants using my instructions.

18
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
 In part two, in this video, we start drafting the pants.

19
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,000
 I will first draft the pants for the standard figure, then show a different way of shaping the waist

20
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:22,000
 for a figure that has a proportionally small waist and upper hips, as in the triangular figure.

21
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:28,000
 I will then draft the pants back for the standard figure, then cover getting the extra crotch length needed for the triangular figure.

22
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:33,000
 In part three, I will go through shaping the waist, the front and the back for the other two figure types,

23
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:37,000
 the Jane and Anne, the square and apples shaped figures.

24
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,000
 Now I'm not covering every single figure type and every single permutation,

25
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:48,000
 but if you watch all the examples, you should get a basic understanding of how to approach solving the problems related to your particular figure.

26
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:51,000
 Okay, now let's start drafting the block.

27
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 Using your waist to ankle measurement, taken down the side of your body, not the front or the back,

28
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
 draw a vertical line down the middle of your paper from A to B.

29
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 At right angles to the A to B line, draw horizontal guard lines across the paper at the waist level and at the ankle level.

30
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 Make sure these lines are at right angles to the A to B line.

31
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:19,000
 Measure down from point A for your high hip placement. That's four or five inches depending on your height and mark the high hip placement.

32
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:25,000
 Draw a guard line across the paper, make sure that it is at right angles to the vertical line.

33
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 Using your waist to low hip measurement, measure down from point A and mark the low hip placement.

34
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:35,000
 Draw a guard line across the paper at right angles to the vertical line.

35
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:41,000
 Now a lot of block making instructions to find the low hip is the widest part of your body.

36
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:44,000
 For some people, the widest part of their body is at their high hip or at their crotch level.

37
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 So as I've covered in the measurement section of part one of the video, the low hip measurement needs to be a measurement between your high hip and your crotch level.

38
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:59,000
 Now measure down from A using your crotch depth measurement and draw a crotch depth guideline at right angles to the vertical line.

39
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 Just use your actual crotch depth. We will add the ease to the crotch depth within the process of drafting the block.

40
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:14,000
 Measure down from A using your waist to knee measurement and draw a knee guideline at right angles to the vertical line.

41
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:19,000
 Take your upper thigh measurement. That is your upper thigh at your crotch level as high as you can get.

42
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 And divide it by two and then add three eighths of an inch ease.

43
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:28,000
 Using the total of that calculation, draw a line from C to D on the crotch depth guideline.

44
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:34,000
 With A to B line at the center of that measurement, mark the points C and D.

45
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:46,000
 Now if you're wondering why we are adding so little ease given that we want to end up with between two and a quarter and two and a half inches ease in the thigh, it is because we will add most of the ease to the back thigh.

46
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 Take your knee circumference measurement, divide it by two, then add five eighths of an inch ease.

47
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:00,000
 Measure that amount on the knee line with the A to B line at the center. Mark points E and F as shown.

48
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 Now remember that the knee circumference measurement should be taken with the knee completely bent as in when you are sitting down.

49
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 If you are worried that's not enough ease, note that the back leg is wider than the front so we will end up with just over two inches ease when we're finished.

50
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 Take the measurement E to F on the knee line and minus two inches. Using that total, measure that amount on the ankle line with point B at the center, mark points G and H.

51
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 Now take your low hip measurement and add one inch ease, then divide it by four.

52
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 Using that value on the crotch depth line, measure from point C and mark point I.

53
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:45,000
 Now there is an exception here that applies only to those whose widest part of the hip is right at the crotch level.

54
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 For those people, use that widest measurement, add one inch ease and then divide it by four.

55
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:01,000
 Don't use the actual measurement of the low hip above your crotch level that I asked you in the measurement section to use as your low hip.

56
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 Now draw a line straight up from point I at right angles to the C to D line until it touches the waist, mark point J where it crosses the low hip line, mark point K where it crosses the high hip line and mark point L where it touches the waist.

57
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 Draw a line up from point C to meet the waist line, mark point M where it crosses the low hip line, mark point N where it crosses the high hip line and mark point O where it touches the waist line.

58
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 Draw straight lines from the knee to the ankle, both the out seam from E to G, shown in pink and the in seam, F to H, shown in green.

59
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 Draw straight lines from point C to E, shown in pink and from points D to F, shown in green. These are just guidelines as we will of course want curved lines down from the torso to the knee.

60
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 We will finish off the curving of the leg line after we have finished the foundation.

61
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 And just reminding you of the two terms, foundation which is shaded in yellow and the leg line which is shaded in green. We have up to here so far the skeleton of the structure, the leg line is mainly finished and we just need to draw in the curve from the knee to the thigh.

62
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:16,000
 The main where it still needs to be done is in the foundation where we will shape the waist and draw the crotch curve.

63
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 Now so far I've been drafting the standard figure as in I've been using the measurements for the standard figure while I've been plotting these points. So what you see here is the skeleton of the standard figure.

64
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:34,000
 But from now on whenever I show the block for the standard figure, the structure or the block outline will be in blue.

65
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 Now here I'm showing you my block drafted up to that same point. Whenever I show you my figure, the structure or the block outline will be in orange.

66
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:50,000
 In this figure, Jane's measurements were used. In all future images when I'm drafting for Jane, the structure or the block outline will be in green.

67
00:06:50,000 --> 00:07:00,000
 And finally for Anne. In this figure, the block has been drafted with Anne's measurements. In all future images when I'm drafting for Anne, the structure or the block outlines will be in purple.

68
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:05,000
 So this is the standard figure again. You can tell that because of the blue guidelines.

69
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 I'm going to start shaping the waist, but while I'm concentrating on the foundation, it's enlarged at 200% of what it was before when we were seeing the whole pant leg.

70
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 So you won't see the leg line while we're working on the foundation.

71
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 Actually, we have one more thing to do before we start shaping the waist and this relates to all figure types. Yes, just something I forgot to do as part of the leg line.

72
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:35,000
 We're going to lower the crotch point before we start shaping the waist. From point D, measure down 5/8 of an inch at right angles to the C to D line.

73
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 We are lowering the crotch point for some ease. Mark the crotch point with a dot.

74
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:48,000
 Although I have indicated mine in the image with a green star, that's just to make sure that you can see it. The center of that green star is my crotch point.

75
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:56,000
 Okay, so we need to do some calculations to work out how much excess we have in the waist so we can do our waist shaping and the calculations need to be done by everyone.

76
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:04,000
 Remember that the width of the foundation from M to J is our hip measurement. It's shown by the black arrow.

77
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:12,000
 Currently, the waist from O to L is the same as the hip measurement. So the hip measurement for this block is 42.5 inches.

78
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:20,000
 The waist is 10 inches less than the hip. That's one of the definitions of the standard figure. Therefore, the waist is 32.5 inches.

79
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 We need to add 1 inch ease, wearing ease to the waist. Therefore, our total is 33.5 inches for the whole pat block.

80
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 Divide that by 4 and we get 8 and 3/8 of an inch for this waist. We will need to put a dart in there as well.

81
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 So we'll start shaping from the next slide. On the waistline from point L, measure in half an inch and mark point P.

82
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 Draw a line from point P on the waist to point J on the low hip. This is part of our center front line.

83
00:08:51,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 From point P, measure across on the waistline towards point O for the waist measurement that was calculated previously plus half an inch for a dart. Mark point Q.

84
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 Take your body high hip measurement and add 1 inch for ease, then divide it by 4. Using this total on the high hip line, measure from where the P to J line crosses the high hip line and mark point R.

85
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:26,000
 Using a French curve, you can draw the side seam from point Q at the waist through point R at the high hip to touch point M on the low hip.

86
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:40,000
 Don't draw down to the crotch line yet as that will be blended down to the leg line later. Using a French curve again, draw in the crotch curve from point J to the crotch point, which in my image is indicated by a star.

87
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 A more specific guide to help you draw that curve, continue the LKJ line until it reaches the level of the crotch point.

88
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:56,000
 Draw a horizontal line at right angles to that line to touch the crotch point. The place where those two points meet is marked with the next.

89
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 From X, draw a line at 45 degree angle. The length of that line is 1 and 1/8 of an inch for smaller sizes up to 1 and 3/8 of an inch for larger sizes.

90
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:18,000
 Now this is just a guide. It's more important to get a smooth curve than hit an exact point, so maybe draw that curve, measure it and see if it's within that parameters, those parameters.

91
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:21,000
 And if it is then, yes, you're good to go.

92
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:30,000
 Draw the waist dart centered on point A at the waistline. Make that dart 1/2 an inch wide and 3 1/2 inches long.

93
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 On the out seam, draw a curve from point M on the hip to pass 1/4 of an inch in from point C, so you'll be shaving off a bit off the thigh.

94
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 You'll have to flip the French curve over in order to then draw a curve to blend in to point E at the knee.

95
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
 You currently have a straight line from the crotch point to the knee.

96
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:56,000
 We want to draw an in seam curve that goes in about 3/8 of an inch at about the midpoint of that guideline.

97
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
 You can cut out the block as we will use it to draft the bodice back.

98
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 After you cut it out, notch the block as shown at the high hip, low hip, crotch and knee on both sides, indicated on my image by the little pink notch marks.

99
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 Now you may ask why we didn't check the crotch length. The reason is that with a standard figure, the crotch length usually ends up correct.

100
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 I'm assuming that's the case and I'll be covering how to make adjustments for crotch length with the other figure types.

101
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:30,000
 So back to where we were before we started shaping the waist. This time instead of using the block and the measurements for the standard figure, we used my block and my measurements.

102
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 Now you may ask why we don't just follow the same instructions we did for the standard figure.

103
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:39,000
 Well if I did, this is the shape I would get. Now there are two things that are wrong.

104
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:52,000
 The side seam curve is not ideal, it's just too much of a curve. And actually when I first tried to draft my block more than 10 years ago, when my waist was quite a bit smaller, but my hips were the same, then it was seriously extreme, it was just ridiculous.

105
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:59,000
 The second thing is I end up with about a half an inch of excess ease in the high hip, so that's on top of the ease that I've already put in there.

106
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 So across the whole block, that's 2 inches of excess ease at the high hip level.

107
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:10,000
 So some people might think, well just widen the dart that's there and put in an extra dart.

108
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 So I've done that here and you'll notice that while it solves the side seam curve problem, it doesn't solve the excess fabric at the high hip, in fact it increases the amount of ease at the high hip level.

109
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:29,000
 It might seem that the answer is to increase the lengths of the dart, that way some of the ease is taken out at the high hip level.

110
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 But if I do that, I still haven't taken out enough ease at the high hip. The second thing is I don't like those long darts, particularly in those places because of other issues with my body.

111
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:44,000
 So for me, this doesn't really work either.

112
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:54,000
 Now here I'm showing you the three places that you can take out the excess, not just the side seam and the dart or darts, you can also take out some excess at the center front.

113
00:12:54,000 --> 00:13:01,000
 So instead of just moving in half an inch from L at the waistline, you move in more. It could be 3/4 of an inch, 1 inch or even more.

114
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:08,000
 The reason for taking it from the center front is that you can take out more lower down, like you can at the side seam.

115
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 Now this portion taken out at the center front, shown in yellow in this image, it's a dart equivalent.

116
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:21,000
 It's putting the dart into a seam line, that's what princess seams do. Rather than having an actual dart, you place the dart value into a seam line.

117
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:27,000
 Generally, it's more flattering and it does away with dart points. So if your figure has this triangular shape, it works better.

118
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 It's more flattering to take more off the center front and the side seam rather than have long darts.

119
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:45,000
 Now I actually watched a tutorial on pants where the tutor said that the sign of good pants pattern is where the center front is on a vertical line, like example A, rather than tilted over, like example B.

120
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:51,000
 The tutor was saying that there are a lot of patterns using the tilt of B, but she was suggesting it was poor pattern making.

121
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 I'd like to vehemently disagree. The tilt does not show poor pattern making, it shows the shape of the figure that the garment has been designed for.

122
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:11,000
 In the process of trying to get pants to fit and look good on me, I took apart quite a few pants, in particular those ones that most suited me on looked good on me, and suited my figure and fit to some extent.

123
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:23,000
 They all had that tilt. The only possible problem with that tilt is because it's no longer on the straight of grain, like in figure A, that when you put a zip in, it could be a bit biopsy.

124
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:27,000
 To solve that problem, you just make sure that you stabilize that seam.

125
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:34,000
 So this is my block and I have come in an inch and a half from center front from LTP, and that works well for me.

126
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 I tried lots of variations, spreading it out between the center front, the side seam and a dart in the middle, and this is what works well for me.

127
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:50,000
 Now another point on this, although this amount, one and a half inches, and the tilt that results from that one and a half inches may seem extreme.

128
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:59,000
 If we compare it to the standard block, and I've laid the standard block on top of mine, the standard blocks of blue, mine's the orange, the angle of that line isn't that extreme.

129
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:09,000
 It's only a half an inch in more than the standard block. It's my short crotch length that's making the angle of the center front look more extreme when it's by itself.

130
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:21,000
 And when I'm talking about the angle, I'm talking about it in context of the grain line on the pants and how biopsy that angle will be, given that in most cases the zip is put in the front.

131
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:29,000
 Now just a couple of final things on that angle of the center front line for the triangular figure in case you're thinking it's a bit too much on an angle.

132
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:37,000
 If the straight of grain is at 90 degrees, the slope line on the standard block is actually 92 degrees and mine is 96 degrees.

133
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:42,000
 Given that the bias is on 135 degrees, the slope on my block is really not an issue.

134
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:48,000
 Remember also that you often put zips in the back and that is always on an angle unless you have a completely flat backside.

135
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 I just want to point out something about the shaping of my block which might seem odd, somebody might notice.

136
00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:07,000
 In taking out that huge dart as it were at the center front, I've gone right down and cut into the lower hip, so I've taken off some of my low hip measurement, but I have put it on the other side at the side seam.

137
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:14,000
 Now if you do use the center front as a dark value for the triangular figure, note that the line from p to j is a straight line.

138
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:21,000
 It starts curving after j after the hip line. It needs to curve after the hip, obviously to go between your legs and join the back.

139
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:25,000
 But the line from p to j needs to be straight so you can put a zip in there.

140
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:33,000
 And obviously as I said before, stabilize that seam line, stabilize it before you put the zip in so there's not going to be a problem if it's a little bit biopsy.

141
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:38,000
 So I have shaped my waist and now I will measure the crotch length from d to p.

142
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 The measurement from d to p is longer than my body front crotch length.

143
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:46,000
 So I will measure up from point d and stop when I reach my measurement.

144
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:50,000
 So then I've reshaped the waistline curve from o down to that point.

145
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:56,000
 Now usually the front crotch length on ready to wear pants and commercial patterns is far too long for me.

146
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:01,000
 The reason I only had a small amount to shave off the top is that I have drafted the pants to my thigh measurement.

147
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:09,000
 If I had drafted it with a crotch extension that it's calculated on the width of the hip, I would have 1 and 5/8 of an inch more as shown.

148
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:18,000
 The pant front I have been drafting for the standard figure has the same hip measurement as I do but the front crotch length is this much wider, this 1 and 5/8 inch.

149
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:22,000
 The dotted blue line, shown in the image, is the crotch front of the standard block.

150
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:26,000
 I will then do the leg shaping as I showed you for the standard block.

151
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:29,000
 I won't repeat that because that is actually the same process.

152
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:37,000
 So this is my final pant front with the waist curve redone and I've also done the leg line shaping but you can't see the whole leg at this point.

153
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:45,000
 So now we move on to drafting the pants back. These steps will apply to all figures but you do need to have your front drafted before doing your back.

154
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,000
 I will be using the standard figure measurements to start with.

155
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 As we will have to flip the front block over, you'll need to notch the key points so that when it's upside down you can see whether upper hip line is, whether hip line is, where the knee line is.

156
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:01,000
 So the notch lines are shown here on the front block.

157
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:05,000
 You will need all the same basic guidelines as for the pants front.

158
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:09,000
 I won't repeat all of that again with the step-by-step detail I did for the front.

159
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 To summarize, draw a vertical line down the middle of the paper and mark A and B.

160
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:24,000
 Then measure down and draw all the placement guidelines for the waist, the high hip, the low hip, the crotch depth, the knee and the ankle.

161
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:31,000
 So draw a line on the crotch depth thigh line from C to D centered on the A to B line.

162
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:39,000
 The length of that line will be your upper thigh measurement divided by 2 plus 3 1/8 of an inch.

163
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:47,000
 Now somebody paying attention might immediately say, but I thought we were supposed to have 2 1/2 inches ease maximum for the slack.

164
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:52,000
 We added 5/8 to the front so this will make the ease 3 1/4 inches not 2 1/2.

165
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:57,000
 It will work out. I'll show you briefly in the next slide to set your mind at ease.

166
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:01,000
 If you look at the pink lines, they have the measurements we're working with.

167
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:06,000
 Our thigh measurement plus ease, but the green lines show where the final thigh measurements would be measured.

168
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 I've got some yellow highlighting to show you the bits that will lose from this original thigh bus plus 3 3/8 of an inch

169
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 and will end up with something like 2 1/4 or 2 1/2 inches ease in the actual upper thigh.

170
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:30,000
 Using the front block knee width measurement plus 1 inch mark points ENF on the knee line with the A to B line at the center.

171
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:35,000
 The pant back is 1 inch wider than the pant front from the knee down.

172
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:45,000
 Using the front block ankle width measurement plus 1 inch mark points G and H on the ankle guard line with the A to B line at the center.

173
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 Using your low hip measurement plus 1 inch ease divided by 4 measure from D towards C and mark point I from I to C is your back extension.

174
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 Draw a vertical line up from point I at right angles to the C to D line.

175
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:10,000
 Mark point J where the line crosses the low hip line, mark point K where it crosses the high hip line and mark point L where it touches the waist.

176
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:22,000
 Now draw a vertical line up from point D, mark point M where it crosses the low hip line, mark point M where it crosses the high hip line and mark point O where it touches the waist.

177
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:31,000
 Draw straight lines from the knee to the ankle from knee point E to ankle point G and from knee point F to ankle point H.

178
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:41,000
 Draw a short guideline about 2 inches long down from point C at right angles to the C to D line. Take your front block and turn it upside down.

179
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:46,000
 Match the in seam knee point of the front with a knee line at the pants back.

180
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:51,000
 Then rotate the front block until the crotch point touches the guideline that comes down from point C.

181
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:56,000
 Trace that front inner leg curve from the crotch point down to the knee.

182
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 Of course your block won't be semi-transparent like mine, I'm using transparency to make it easier for you to see what's going on.

183
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:12,000
 Setting aside the pant front for a minute, on the pant back measure in from point D for a quarter of an inch and mark point D too.

184
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:17,000
 So bring the front block back again and flip it over so you can match up the side seams.

185
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:23,000
 Match the knee line of the front block with a knee line of the back block at point F.

186
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:29,000
 Rotate the front block so that it passes through point D too and touches the low hip at point M.

187
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:33,000
 Trace that front block from point F to point M.

188
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:42,000
 Now rotate the front block so that the crotch, low hip, high hip and waist lines match up and the front is exactly on top of the back at those key points.

189
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:49,000
 Trace the front side seam line from the low hip point M to the waist and label point P.

190
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:53,000
 We need to use the same waist measurement as we did for the pants front.

191
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:57,000
 That is the waist plus one inch E's divided by four.

192
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:05,000
 Measure across from point P for that waist measurement plus three quarters of an inch for the back dart and mark point Q.

193
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:10,000
 Measure up from point Q for three quarters of an inch and mark point R.

194
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:14,000
 Make sure that when you measure up it's at right angles to the horizontal line.

195
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:23,000
 Draw the waist line from point P to point R. Now continue the line down from L on the waist line, that's that L K J I line.

196
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:26,000
 Continue it down below the crotch for a few inches.

197
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:32,000
 Draw a horizontal line at right angles to that line you've just drawn that touches the crotch point.

198
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:36,000
 I have marked the intersection of those two lines with an X.

199
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:42,000
 Mark point S, halfway between point L on the waist and the crotch depth up a thigh line.

200
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:49,000
 Draw a straight line from R at the waist to pass through point S and touch the low hip guideline.

201
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:54,000
 It should touch the low hip guideline a little to the left of point J.

202
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:58,000
 Then draw a curve from the crotch point to meet that point.

203
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:04,000
 To check that curve, if you draw a line from point X at 45 degrees to the horizontal and vertical lines,

204
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:11,000
 it should be between 1 and 11/16 inches long for smaller sizes and 2 inches long for larger sizes.

205
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:15,000
 If it's between those two lengths and it's a smooth curve, then it's okay.

206
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:22,000
 In the center of the back waist line, create a dart that's 3/4 of an inch wide and 4 1/2 inches long.

207
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:27,000
 Before cutting out the back block, you'll need to double check the side seams and the inseam lengths.

208
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:31,000
 If the back side seam is a touch longer than the front, you can equalize the difference.

209
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:35,000
 Again, I haven't checked the crotch length of the back for this standard figure.

210
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:40,000
 I will be showing you how to increase or decrease the crotch length when drafting my block.

211
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:46,000
 The final thing you need to do is check the flow through of the crotch curve from front to back.

212
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:50,000
 You may want to create clean copies of your block, especially if you've drafted them onto paper

213
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:53,000
 and want to now create a more durable cardboard copy.

214
00:23:53,000 --> 00:24:00,000
 Having said that, you may want to first test your block by making a twile and waiting till you've perfected it to create a final cardboard copy.

215
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:05,000
 Don't forget to notch and label your block. I will now continue with drafting my back block.

216
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:10,000
 So I'm starting with my pant back guard lines and my pant front.

217
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:18,000
 So from here, I'll be repeating the same steps as I did for the standard block until we get to shaping the waist.

218
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:22,000
 So I'll just briefly cover them. I will draw the lines from the knees to the ankle.

219
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:31,000
 Using the front block, I will trace the inseam after having drawn a guideline down from point C and at right angles to the C to D line.

220
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:40,000
 I will line up the front block on the knee line and pivot until the crotch touches point D2, which is a quarter of an inch in from point D.

221
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:43,000
 Then trace the front side seam up to the hip point M.

222
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:49,000
 I'll move the front block to line up the horizontal lines, the hip line, the low hip, high hip, etc.

223
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:56,000
 And trace the front block from point M at the hip up to the waist line and mark point P.

224
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:01,000
 I will measure across from point P for my waist measurement plus a three quarter inch dart.

225
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:05,000
 That waist measurement is the body waist plus an inch E's divided by four,

226
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:10,000
 the same as the pant front before the dart value was added for the pant's front.

227
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:14,000
 The back waist will end up being a quarter of an inch more in total than the front,

228
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:18,000
 as the front has a half an inch dart and the back has a three quarter inch dart.

229
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:25,000
 I will measure across from the side seam on the high hip line for the same high hip measurement used on the front and mark point S.

230
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:30,000
 That measurement is the body hip, high hip plus an inch E's divided by four.

231
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:36,000
 Now I'm not actually going to use this point to draft the back crotch line,

232
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:42,000
 but it's there to show me how much extra E's is there, if there's any extra E's.

233
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 I might be able to take it off at the side seam if there is, I might not.

234
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:50,000
 This is just purely for interest to see whether I do end up with too much E's there.

235
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:56,000
 I'm continuing the line from L at the waist that goes down through K and J and I.

236
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 I'm continuing that line further down for a few inches.

237
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:03,000
 Then drawing another line at right angles to that line to touch the crotch point.

238
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:06,000
 I've marked the intersection with an X.

239
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:12,000
 I have drawn a straight line from point R above the waist to point J on the low hip.

240
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:17,000
 Using a French curve, I have then drawn a curve from the crotch point to meet that line.

241
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:22,000
 After drawing the curve, I have measured the full crotch length line from point R to the crotch point.

242
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:27,000
 Mine is far too short, so I will have to increase the length by cutting and spreading.

243
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:32,000
 If you are increasing the length of your crotch, or actually if you are decreasing it also,

244
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:34,000
 you need to cut the paper.

245
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:37,000
 If you're increasing it, you'll need other paper to put underneath.

246
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 If you're decreasing it, you won't need that extra paper.

247
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:47,000
 Cut along the crotch depth line from the edge of the paper to point D2 cut to D2 but not through that point.

248
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:51,000
 Then cut from the other side of the paper to intersect at the J point at the low hip line

249
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:54,000
 and through up to the D2 point.

250
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:57,000
 Don't cut through completely, leave a small hinge.

251
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:02,000
 It's better if you draw a straight line with the ruler and then cut along that line.

252
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:07,000
 Now place another piece of paper underneath and spread to get the extra length you need.

253
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:10,000
 You may have to spread it, measure it, adjust, re-measure.

254
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:13,000
 You may need to test it a few times before you get your correct length.

255
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:17,000
 You can also decrease your crotch length by overlapping instead of opening.

256
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:20,000
 I'll do just a slight detail from my block to cover that.

257
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 For a flat bottom, pivot and overlap the paper to shorten the length of the crotch.

258
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:29,000
 For a flatter bottom, you can scoop out the curve.

259
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 This will result in less fabric in the pad, but notice that it does increase the length of the crotch,

260
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:40,000
 so you may have to overlap a bit more if scooping it out has lengthened it too much.

261
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:43,000
 If you have a completely flat bottom, no bottom at all,

262
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:48,000
 you can decrease the length of the crotch further by reducing the slope of the centre back seam.

263
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:56,000
 So I pushed it out to the left and made it straighter instead of being on the angle that it was before.

264
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:00,000
 Now if you do make this kind of adjustment, then you've increased your waist.

265
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:06,000
 So from the purple line to the dashed red line, that's extra amount in the waist,

266
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:08,000
 which you'll need to account for somewhere.

267
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:14,000
 So either put in a dart to that value in the pant or take it off the side seam.

268
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:20,000
 Getting back to my figure, or a large bottom that needs lengthening in the back crotch,

269
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:26,000
 I'll let you know that I will not actually be using point R, which is 3/4 of an inch above the waist.

270
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:33,000
 To draw my back seam, I'm actually going to draw it from point Q, which was the original straight waistline.

271
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:36,000
 I'll show you what difference that makes.

272
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:41,000
 So in this example, I have drawn my back seam from point R, which is not what I'm going to do for my block,

273
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:45,000
 but I want to show you what happens if I do use point R.

274
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:47,000
 I want you to look at two things.

275
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:52,000
 Firstly, to the right, I have put the two pat legs together and matched up the back seam

276
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:56,000
 for the portion that it is straight from the waist to the hip.

277
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:59,000
 And I want you to notice the first thing is the straight line on the waist.

278
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:01,000
 It's completely parallel.

279
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:05,000
 Secondly, look at the amount that I have inserted down in the seat of the pants.

280
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:09,000
 On the left-hand side, shown by the teal green wedge.

281
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:13,000
 So just look at that green teal wedge as the next slide appears.

282
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:16,000
 So you can see in this one that the wedge portion has increased.

283
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:21,000
 So I've actually put more of that length down in the seat of the pants,

284
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:24,000
 and I'm not putting it up above the waist.

285
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:28,000
 And on the right-hand side, you can see the yellow pad, which is this one,

286
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 how it's got a curve to the waist.

287
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:35,000
 The crotch length is actually exactly the same, but I just prefer this option.

288
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:39,000
 On this toil, which is on my dressmaker's dummy, made from a cast of my body,

289
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:44,000
 I've colored in the amount that has been added in the extra crotch length that I've gained

290
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:47,000
 in making the adjustment I've just showed you.

291
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:52,000
 So compared to the standard figure, I need this much more length in the back of my pant.

292
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,000
 Now, just in case you do notice that it's not sitting really at my waist,

293
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:56,000
 it's sitting a bit below.

294
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:00,000
 It's because I've put on weight in my waistline since this cast was made.

295
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:03,000
 So in real life, this does actually sit right up at my waist.

296
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:06,000
 So on the right are the two shapes compared.

297
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:12,000
 The yellow one is the one that I use, where I draw my back curve from the lower point

298
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
 and the blue one is drawing it from the higher point.

299
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:21,000
 So I have to finish off my waist by drawing the waistline from P to Q, rather than to R.

300
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:26,000
 And I have to put in my dart, which isn't in the middle, like the standard directions say.

301
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:30,000
 Mine is actually a bit longer also than the standard directions, given the shape of my body.

302
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:34,000
 Dark placement is a personal thing, depending on your body and your preference.

303
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:37,000
 I will also have to smooth out the side scene.

304
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:40,000
 So here's my pants front and pants back once I've finished.

305
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:46,000
 So here's a comparison of the standard block and my block, both of them made with the same hip measurement.

306
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:50,000
 And I still have to finish the video of drafting Jane and Anne's blocks.

307
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:52,000
 I will do that as soon as I can.

308
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:57,000
 One final thing before finishing this video, I want to say something about expectation and bagginess.

309
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:02,000
 A lot of people seem to think that getting rid of all the bagginess in the backfire is essential.

310
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:08,000
 But for some people, with a certain figure, it's a fool's errand trying to achieve this in the basic pants block.

311
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:11,000
 That is, just the two pattern pieces and in woven fabric.

312
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:18,000
 Now if you have the standard figure with a smallish bottom, you might get a really well-fitting block with no bagginess in the upper thigh.

313
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:25,000
 If you have the kind of figure with a small upper thigh in proportion to your hips, and especially if you've got an overhanging bottom, you will have problems.

314
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:32,000
 Now think about it, the length you need for a pant where you're standing up is different to the length you need when you're sitting down and moving.

315
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:41,000
 Now in the image with the blue arrows, when this body sits down, the length she needs is a lot longer than the length she needs standing up.

316
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:44,000
 If you have bagginess in your upper thigh, try this.

317
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:47,000
 Measure the length from your waist to the floor standing up.

318
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:51,000
 Then measure your length while sitting down and see how much more length you need.

319
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:55,000
 I need something like four inches and that's no exaggeration.

320
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:02,000
 I say this because if you have my type of figure, you could take a fish-eyed dart out and get rid of all the bagginess while standing up.

321
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:07,000
 But when you sit down, the pants will ride halfway up your calf and it's not a good look.

322
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:18,000
 If you want to get rid of bagginess, sewing with stretch fabric and putting vertical design lines, where you can take up some of the width rather than the length, is a better option.

323
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:23,000
 So that's the end of this video. This is Maria from Dress Pattern Making. Ciao.

